Labeled extends Control

Description
A Labeled Control is one which has as part of its user interface a textual content associated with it. For example, a Button displays text, as does a Label, a Tooltip, and many other controls.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-alignment [ top-left | top-center | top-right | center-left | center | center-right bottom-left | bottom-center | bottom-right | baseline-left | baseline-center | baseline-right ] top-level Specifies how the text and graphic within the Labeled should be aligned when there is empty space within the Labeled.
-fx-text-alignment [ left | center | right | justify ] left

Specifies the behavior for lines of text when text is multiline

Unlike contentDisplayProperty which affects the graphic and text, this setting only affects multiple lines of text relative to the text bounds.
-fx-text-overrun [ center-ellipsis | center-word-ellipsis | clip | ellipsis | leading-ellipsis | leading-word-ellipsis | word-ellipsis ] ellipsis Specifies the behavior to use if the text of the Labeled exceeds the available space for rendering the text.
-fx-wrap-text <boolean> false If a run of text exceeds the width of the Labeled, then this variable indicates whether the text should wrap onto another line.
-fx-font <font> null The default font to use for text in the Labeled. If the Label's text is rich text then this font may or may not be used depending on the font information embedded in the rich text, but in any case where a default font is required, this font will be used.
-fx-underline <boolean> false Whether all text should be underlined.
-fx-graphic <uri> null Image url
-fx-content-display [ top | right | bottom | left | center | right | graphic-only | text-only ] left Specifies the positioning of the graphic relative to the text.
-fx-graphic-text-gap <size> 4 The amount of space between the graphic and text
-fx-label-padding <size> | <size> <size> <size> <size> 0.0

The padding around the Labeled's text and graphic content.

By default labelPadding is Insets.EMPTY and cannot be set to null.

Subclasses may add nodes outside this padding and inside the Labeled's padding.
-fx-text-fill <paint> BLACK The Paint used to fill the text.
-fx-ellipsis-string <string> "..." Specifies the string to display for the ellipsis when text is truncated.
Examples
"..." - Default value for most locales
" . . . "
" [...] "
"\u2026" - The Unicode ellipsis character '…'
"" - No ellipsis, just display the truncated string

Note that not all fonts support all Unicode characters.

ButtonBase extends Labeled

Description
Base class for button-like UI Controls, including Hyperlinks, Buttons, ToggleButtons, CheckBoxes, and RadioButtons. The primary contribution of ButtonBase is providing a consistent API for handling the concept of button "arming". In UIs, a button will typically only "fire" if some user gesture occurs while the button is "armed". For example, a Button may be armed if the mouse is pressed and the Button is enabled and the mouse is over the button. In such a situation, if the mouse is then released, then the Button is "fired", meaning its action takes place.

ComboBoxBase extends Control

Description
Abstract base class for ComboBox-like controls. A ComboBox typically has a button that, when clicked, will pop up some means of allowing a user to select one or more values (depending on the implementation). This base class makes no assumptions about what happens when the show() and hide() methods are called, however commonly this results in either a popup or dialog appearing that allows for the user to provide the required information.

Button extends ButtonBase

Description
A simple button control. The button control can contain text and/or a graphic. A button control has three different modes

  • Normal: A normal push button.
  • Default: A default Button is the button that receives a keyboard VK_ENTER press, if no other node in the scene consumes it.
  • Cancel: A Cancel Button is the button that receives a keyboard VK_ESC press, if no other node in the scene consumes it.

-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.
-fx-translate-x double 0.0 Defines the x coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-y double 0.0 Defines the y coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-z double 0.0 Defines the z coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
visibility <visibility> visible
Control -fx-skin <string> null The class name of the Control's Skin.

Name Definition

:default applies if this Button receives VK_ENTER if the event is not otherwise consumed

ButtonBase :armed applies when the armed variable is true

Cell extends Labeled

Description

The Cell API is used for virtualized controls such as ListView, TreeView, and TableView.

A Cell is a Labeled Control, and is used to render a single "row" inside a ListView, TreeView or TableView. Cells are also used for each individual 'cell' inside a TableView (i.e. each row/column intersection). See the JavaDoc for each control separately for more detail.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-cell-size <size> 15 The cell size. For vertical ListView or a TreeView or TableView this is the height, for a horizontal ListView this is the width.
Inherited Properties
Element Property Definition Default Description
Labeled -fx-alignment [ top-left | top-center | top-right | center-left | center | center-right bottom-left | bottom-center | bottom-right | baseline-left | baseline-center | baseline-right ] top-level Specifies how the text and graphic within the Labeled should be aligned when there is empty space within the Labeled.
-fx-text-alignment [ left | center | right | justify ] left

Specifies the behavior for lines of text when text is multiline

Unlike contentDisplayProperty which affects the graphic and text, this setting only affects multiple lines of text relative to the text bounds.
-fx-text-overrun [ center-ellipsis | center-word-ellipsis | clip | ellipsis | leading-ellipsis | leading-word-ellipsis | word-ellipsis ] ellipsis Specifies the behavior to use if the text of the Labeled exceeds the available space for rendering the text.
-fx-wrap-text <boolean> false If a run of text exceeds the width of the Labeled, then this variable indicates whether the text should wrap onto another line.
-fx-font <font> null The default font to use for text in the Labeled. If the Label's text is rich text then this font may or may not be used depending on the font information embedded in the rich text, but in any case where a default font is required, this font will be used.
-fx-underline <boolean> false Whether all text should be underlined.
-fx-graphic <uri> null Image url
-fx-content-display [ top | right | bottom | left | center | right | graphic-only | text-only ] left Specifies the positioning of the graphic relative to the text.
-fx-graphic-text-gap <size> 4 The amount of space between the graphic and text
-fx-label-padding <size> | <size> <size> <size> <size> 0.0

The padding around the Labeled's text and graphic content.

By default labelPadding is Insets.EMPTY and cannot be set to null.

Subclasses may add nodes outside this padding and inside the Labeled's padding.
-fx-text-fill <paint> BLACK The Paint used to fill the text.
-fx-ellipsis-string <string> "..." Specifies the string to display for the ellipsis when text is truncated.
Examples
"..." - Default value for most locales
" . . . "
" [...] "
"\u2026" - The Unicode ellipsis character '…'
"" - No ellipsis, just display the truncated string

Note that not all fonts support all Unicode characters.
Control -fx-skin <string> null The class name of the Control's Skin.

-fx-cursor <cursor> null Defines the mouse cursor for this Node and subnodes
-fx-effect <effect> null Specifies an effect to apply to this Node
-fx-focus-traversable <boolean> null Specifies whether this Node should be a part of focus traversal cycle
-fx-opacity double 1.0 Opacity can be thought of conceptually as a postprocessing operation. Conceptually, after the node (including its descendants) is rendered into an RGBA offscreen image, the opacity setting specifies how to blend the offscreen rendering into the current composite rendering.
-fx-rotate double 0.0 This is the angle of the rotation in degrees. Zero degrees is at 3 o'clock (directly to the right). Angle values are positive clockwise. Rotation is about the center.
-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-y double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Y axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.

CheckBox extends ButtonBase

Description
A tri-state selection Control typically skinned as a box with a checkmark or tick mark when checked. A CheckBox control can be in one of three states:
  • checked: indeterminate == false, checked == true
  • unchecked: indeterminate == false, checked == false
  • undefined: indeterminate == true

ChoiceBox extends Control

Description
The ChoiceBox is used for presenting the user with a relatively small set of predefined choices from which they may choose. The ChoiceBox, when "showing", will display to the user these choices and allow them to pick exactly one choice. When not showing, the current choice is displayed.

ComboBox

Description
An implementation of the ComboBoxBase abstract class for the most common form of ComboBox, where a popup list is shown to users providing them with a choice that they may select from. For more information around the general concepts and API of ComboBox, refer to the ComboBoxBase class documentation.

Hyperlink extends ButtonBase

Description
An HTML like label which can be a graphic and/or text which responds to rollovers and clicks. When a hyperlink is clicked/pressed isVisited becomes true. A Hyperlink behaves just like a Button. When a hyperlink is pressed and released a ActionEvent is sent, and your application can perform some action based on this event.

IndexedCell extends Cell

Description
An implementation of Cell which contains an index property which maps into the data model underlying the visualization. Despite this, IndexedCell should not be instantiated directly in a cell factory (refer to Cell for more details on what a cell factory is). Instead of creating IndexedCell directly, you should instead make use of the control-specific cell implementations (for example, ListCell, TreeCell) TableRow and TableCell). For more information about using and customizing cells, refer to the {@link Cell} API documentation.

Label extends Labeled

Description
Label is a non-editable text control. A Label is useful for displaying text that is required to fit within a specific space, and thus may need to use an ellipsis or truncation to size the string to fit. Labels also are useful in that they can have mnemonics which, if used, will send focus to the Control listed as the target of the labelFor property.

"" - No ellipsis, just display the truncated string

Note that not all fonts support all Unicode characters.

-fx-effect <effect> null Specifies an effect to apply to this Node
-fx-focus-traversable <boolean> null Specifies whether this Node should be a part of focus traversal cycle
-fx-opacity double 1.0 Opacity can be thought of conceptually as a postprocessing operation. Conceptually, after the node (including its descendants) is rendered into an RGBA offscreen image, the opacity setting specifies how to blend the offscreen rendering into the current composite rendering.
-fx-rotate double 0.0 This is the angle of the rotation in degrees. Zero degrees is at 3 o'clock (directly to the right). Angle values are positive clockwise. Rotation is about the center.
-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-y double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Y axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.

ListCell extends IndexedCell

Description
The Cell type used within ListView instances. In addition to the API defined on Cell and IndexedCell, the ListCell is more tightly bound to a ListView, allowing for better support of editing events, etc.
Inherited Properties
Element Property Definition Default Description
Labeled -fx-alignment [ top-left | top-center | top-right | center-left | center | center-right bottom-left | bottom-center | bottom-right | baseline-left | baseline-center | baseline-right ] top-level Specifies how the text and graphic within the Labeled should be aligned when there is empty space within the Labeled.
-fx-text-alignment [ left | center | right | justify ] left

Specifies the behavior for lines of text when text is multiline

Unlike contentDisplayProperty which affects the graphic and text, this setting only affects multiple lines of text relative to the text bounds.
-fx-text-overrun [ center-ellipsis | center-word-ellipsis | clip | ellipsis | leading-ellipsis | leading-word-ellipsis | word-ellipsis ] ellipsis Specifies the behavior to use if the text of the Labeled exceeds the available space for rendering the text.
-fx-wrap-text <boolean> false If a run of text exceeds the width of the Labeled, then this variable indicates whether the text should wrap onto another line.
-fx-font <font> null The default font to use for text in the Labeled. If the Label's text is rich text then this font may or may not be used depending on the font information embedded in the rich text, but in any case where a default font is required, this font will be used.
-fx-underline <boolean> false Whether all text should be underlined.
-fx-graphic <uri> null Image url
-fx-content-display [ top | right | bottom | left | center | right | graphic-only | text-only ] left Specifies the positioning of the graphic relative to the text.
-fx-graphic-text-gap <size> 4 The amount of space between the graphic and text
-fx-label-padding <size> | <size> <size> <size> <size> 0.0

The padding around the Labeled's text and graphic content.

By default labelPadding is Insets.EMPTY and cannot be set to null.

Subclasses may add nodes outside this padding and inside the Labeled's padding.

-fx-ellipsis-string <string> "..." Specifies the string to display for the ellipsis when text is truncated.

"" - No ellipsis, just display the truncated string

ListView extends Control

Description
A ListView displays a horizontal or vertical list of items from which the user may select, or with which the user may interact. A ListView is able to have its generic type set to represent the type of data in the backing model. Doing this has the benefit of making various methods in the ListView, as well as the supporting classes (mentioned below), type-safe. In addition, making use of the generic supports substantially simplifies development of applications making use of ListView, as all modern IDEs are able to auto-complete far more successfully with the additional type information.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-orientation [ horizontal | vertical ] horizontal The orientation of the ListView - this can either be horizontal or vertical.
Inherited Properties

-fx-focus-traversable <boolean> null Specifies whether this Node should be a part of focus traversal cycle
-fx-opacity double 1.0 Opacity can be thought of conceptually as a postprocessing operation. Conceptually, after the node (including its descendants) is rendered into an RGBA offscreen image, the opacity setting specifies how to blend the offscreen rendering into the current composite rendering.
-fx-rotate double 0.0 This is the angle of the rotation in degrees. Zero degrees is at 3 o'clock (directly to the right). Angle values are positive clockwise. Rotation is about the center.
-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-y double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Y axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.

Menu extends Control

Description
A popup menu of actionable items which is displayed to the user only upon request. When a menu is visible, in most use cases, the user can select one menu item before the menu goes back to its hidden state. This means the menu is a good place to put important functionality that does not necessarily need to be visible at all times to the user.

RadioButton extends ToggleButton

Description
RadioButtons create a series of items where only one item can be selected. RadioButtons are a specialized ToggleButton. When a RadioButton is pressed and released a javafx.event.ActionEvent is sent. Your application can perform some action based on this event by implementing an javafx.event.EventHandler to process the javafx.event.ActionEvent.
Inherited Properties
Element Property Definition Default Description
Labeled -fx-alignment [ top-left | top-center | top-right | center-left | center | center-right bottom-left | bottom-center | bottom-right | baseline-left | baseline-center | baseline-right ] top-level Specifies how the text and graphic within the Labeled should be aligned when there is empty space within the Labeled.
-fx-text-alignment [ left | center | right | justify ] left

Specifies the behavior for lines of text when text is multiline

Unlike contentDisplayProperty which affects the graphic and text, this setting only affects multiple lines of text relative to the text bounds.
-fx-text-overrun [ center-ellipsis | center-word-ellipsis | clip | ellipsis | leading-ellipsis | leading-word-ellipsis | word-ellipsis ] ellipsis Specifies the behavior to use if the text of the Labeled exceeds the available space for rendering the text.
-fx-wrap-text <boolean> false If a run of text exceeds the width of the Labeled, then this variable indicates whether the text should wrap onto another line.
-fx-font <font> null The default font to use for text in the Labeled. If the Label's text is rich text then this font may or may not be used depending on the font information embedded in the rich text, but in any case where a default font is required, this font will be used.
-fx-underline <boolean> false Whether all text should be underlined.
-fx-graphic <uri> null Image url
-fx-content-display [ top | right | bottom | left | center | right | graphic-only | text-only ] left Specifies the positioning of the graphic relative to the text.
-fx-graphic-text-gap <size> 4 The amount of space between the graphic and text
-fx-label-padding <size> | <size> <size> <size> <size> 0.0

The padding around the Labeled's text and graphic content.

By default labelPadding is Insets.EMPTY and cannot be set to null.

Subclasses may add nodes outside this padding and inside the Labeled's padding.
-fx-text-fill <paint> BLACK The Paint used to fill the text.
-fx-ellipsis-string <string> "..." Specifies the string to display for the ellipsis when text is truncated.
Examples
"..." - Default value for most locales
" . . . "
" [...] "
"\u2026" - The Unicode ellipsis character '…'
"" - No ellipsis, just display the truncated string

Note that not all fonts support all Unicode characters.
Control -fx-skin <string> null The class name of the Control's Skin.
Node -fx-blend-mode <blend-mode> null The mode used to blend this individual node into the scene behind it
-fx-cursor <cursor> null Defines the mouse cursor for this Node and subnodes
-fx-effect <effect> null Specifies an effect to apply to this Node
-fx-focus-traversable <boolean> null Specifies whether this Node should be a part of focus traversal cycle
-fx-opacity double 1.0 Opacity can be thought of conceptually as a postprocessing operation. Conceptually, after the node (including its descendants) is rendered into an RGBA offscreen image, the opacity setting specifies how to blend the offscreen rendering into the current composite rendering.
-fx-rotate double 0.0 This is the angle of the rotation in degrees. Zero degrees is at 3 o'clock (directly to the right). Angle values are positive clockwise. Rotation is about the center.
-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-y double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Y axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.
-fx-translate-x double 0.0 Defines the x coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-y double 0.0 Defines the y coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-z double 0.0 Defines the z coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.

ScrollPane extends Control

Description
A Control that provides a scrolled, clipped viewport of its contents. It allows the user to scroll the content around either directly (panning) or by using scroll bars. The ScrollPane allows specification of the scroll bar policy, which determines when scroll bars are displayed: always, never, or only when they are needed. The scroll bar policy can be specified independently for the horizontal and vertical scroll bars.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-fit-to-width <boolean> false If true and if the contained node is a Resizable, then the node will be kept resized to match the width of the ScrollPane's viewport. If the contained node is not a Resizable, this value is ignored.
-fx-fit-to-height <boolean> false If true and if the contained node is a Resizable, then the node will be kept resized to match the height of the ScrollPane's viewport. If the contained node is not a Resizable, this value is ignored.
-fx-pannable <boolean> false Specifies whether the user should be able to pan the viewport by using the mouse. If mouse events reach the ScrollPane (that is, if mouse events are not blocked by the contained node or one of its children) then pannable is consulted to determine if the events should be used for panning.
-fx-hbar-policy [ never | always | as-needed ] always Specifies the policy for showing the horizontal scroll bar.
-fx-vbar-policy [ never | always | as-needed ] always Specifies the policy for showing the vertical scroll bar.
Inherited Properties
Element Property Definition Default Description
Node -fx-blend-mode <blend-mode> null The mode used to blend this individual node into the scene behind it
-fx-cursor <cursor> null Defines the mouse cursor for this Node and subnodes
-fx-effect <effect> null Specifies an effect to apply to this Node
-fx-focus-traversable <boolean> null Specifies whether this Node should be a part of focus traversal cycle
-fx-opacity double 1.0 Opacity can be thought of conceptually as a postprocessing operation. Conceptually, after the node (including its descendants) is rendered into an RGBA offscreen image, the opacity setting specifies how to blend the offscreen rendering into the current composite rendering.
-fx-rotate double 0.0 This is the angle of the rotation in degrees. Zero degrees is at 3 o'clock (directly to the right). Angle values are positive clockwise. Rotation is about the center.
-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-y double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Y axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.

Slider extends Control

Description
The Slider Control is used to display a continuous or discrete range of valid numeric choices and allows the user to interact with the control. It is typically represented visually as having a "track" and a "knob" or "thumb" which is dragged within the track. The Slider can optionally show tick marks and labels indicating the different slider position values.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-orientation [ horizontal | vertical ] horizontal The orientation
-fx-show-tick-labels <boolean> false Indicates that the labels for tick marks should be shown
-fx-show-tick-marks <boolean> false Specifies whether the Skin implementation should show tick marks.
-fx-major-tick-unit double 25 he unit distance between major tick marks.
-fx-minor-tick-count double 3 The number of minor ticks to place between any two major ticks.
-fx-snap-to-ticks <boolean> false Indicates whether the value of the Slider should always be aligned with the tick marks. This is honored even if the tick marks are not shown.
-fx-block-increment int 10 The amount by which to adjust the slider if the track of the slider is clicked.

Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-tab-min-width int 0.0 The minimum width of the tabs in the TabPane. This can be used to limit the length of text in tabs to prevent truncation. Setting the min equal to the max will fix the width of the tab. By default the min equals to the max.
-fx-tab-max-width int DOUBLE_MAX Specifies the maximum width of a tab. This can be used to limit the length of text in tabs. If the tab text is longer than the maximum width the text will be truncated. Setting the max equal to the min will fix the width of the tab. By default the min equals to the max
-fx-tab-min-height int 0.0 The minimum height of the tabs in the TabPane. This can be used to limit the height in tabs. Setting the min equal to the max will fix the height of the tab. By default the min equals to the max.
-fx-tab-max-height int DOUBLE_MAX The maximum height if the tabs in the TabPane. This can be used to limit the height in tabs. Setting the max equal to the min will fix the height of the tab. By default the min equals to the max.

Labeled -fx-alignment [ top-left | top-center | top-right | center-left | center | center-right bottom-left | bottom-center | bottom-right | baseline-left | baseline-center | baseline-right ] top-level Specifies how the text and graphic within the Labeled should be aligned when there is empty space within the Labeled.
-fx-text-alignment [ left | center | right | justify ] left

Specifies the behavior for lines of text when text is multiline

Unlike contentDisplayProperty which affects the graphic and text, this setting only affects multiple lines of text relative to the text bounds.
-fx-text-overrun [ center-ellipsis | center-word-ellipsis | clip | ellipsis | leading-ellipsis | leading-word-ellipsis | word-ellipsis ] ellipsis Specifies the behavior to use if the text of the Labeled exceeds the available space for rendering the text.
-fx-wrap-text <boolean> false If a run of text exceeds the width of the Labeled, then this variable indicates whether the text should wrap onto another line.
-fx-font <font> null The default font to use for text in the Labeled. If the Label's text is rich text then this font may or may not be used depending on the font information embedded in the rich text, but in any case where a default font is required, this font will be used.
-fx-underline <boolean> false Whether all text should be underlined.
-fx-graphic <uri> null Image url
-fx-content-display [ top | right | bottom | left | center | right | graphic-only | text-only ] left Specifies the positioning of the graphic relative to the text.
-fx-graphic-text-gap <size> 4 The amount of space between the graphic and text
-fx-label-padding <size> | <size> <size> <size> <size> 0.0

The padding around the Labeled's text and graphic content.

By default labelPadding is Insets.EMPTY and cannot be set to null.

Subclasses may add nodes outside this padding and inside the Labeled's padding.
-fx-text-fill <paint> BLACK The Paint used to fill the text.
-fx-ellipsis-string <string> "..." Specifies the string to display for the ellipsis when text is truncated.
Examples
"..." - Default value for most locales
" . . . "
" [...] "
"\u2026" - The Unicode ellipsis character '…'
"" - No ellipsis, just display the truncated string

Note that not all fonts support all Unicode characters.

-fx-effect <effect> null Specifies an effect to apply to this Node
-fx-focus-traversable <boolean> null Specifies whether this Node should be a part of focus traversal cycle
-fx-opacity double 1.0 Opacity can be thought of conceptually as a postprocessing operation. Conceptually, after the node (including its descendants) is rendered into an RGBA offscreen image, the opacity setting specifies how to blend the offscreen rendering into the current composite rendering.
-fx-rotate double 0.0 This is the angle of the rotation in degrees. Zero degrees is at 3 o'clock (directly to the right). Angle values are positive clockwise. Rotation is about the center.
-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.

javafx.scene.charts

AreaChart extends XYChart

Description
AreaChart - Plots the area between the line that connects the data points and the 0 line on the Y axis.
Inherited Properties
Element Property Definition Default Description
Chart -fx-legend-side [ top | left | right | bottom ] bottom the side of the chart where the legend should be displayed
-fx-legend-visible <boolean> true When true the chart will display a legend if the chart implementation supports a legend.
-fx-title-side [ top | left | right | bottom ] top The side of the chart where the title is displayed
Node -fx-blend-mode <blend-mode> null The mode used to blend this individual node into the scene behind it

visibility <visibility> visible
XYChart -fx-alternative-column-fill-visible <boolean> true If true then alternative vertical columns will have fills
-fx-alternative-row-fill-visible <boolean> true If true then alternative horizontal rows will have fills
-fx-horizontal-grid-lines-visible <boolean> true True if horizontal grid lines should be drawn
-fx-horizontal-zero-line-visible <boolean> true If this is true and the horizontal axis has both positive and negative values then a additional axis line will be drawn at the zero point
-fx-vertical-grid-lines-visible <boolean> true True if vertical grid lines should be drawn
-fx-vertical-zero-line-visible <boolean> true If this is true and the vertical axis has both positive and negative values then a additional axis line will be drawn at the zero point
Region -fx-background-color <helper-background-color> null A series of paint values separated by commas.
-fx-background-insets <helper-background-insets> null A series of size values or sets of four size values, separated by commas. A single size value means all insets are the same. Otherwise, the four values for each inset are given in the order top, right, bottom, left. Each comma-separated value or set of values in the series applies to the corresponding background color.
-fx-background-image <helper-background-image> null A series of image URIs separated by commas.
-fx-background-position <helper-background-position> null A series of values separated by commas. Each bg-position item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the background-image series.
-fx-background-repeat <helper-background-repeat> null
-fx-background-size <helper-background-size>
-fx-border-color <helper-border-color> A series of paint values or sets of four paint values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, if a single paint value is specified, then that paint is used as the border for all sides of the region; and if a set of four paints is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left borders of the region, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first paint value in the set is used.
-fx-border-insets <helper-border-insets> A series of inset or sets of four inset values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single inset value means that all insets are the same; and if a set of four inset values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order. Each item in the series of insets applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-radius <helper-border-radius> A series of radius or sets of four radius values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single radius value means that all corner radii are the same; and if a set of four radius values is specified, they are used as the radii of the top-left, top-right, bottom-right, and bottom-left corners, in that order. Each item in the series of radii applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-style <helper-border-style> A series of border style values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors. The segments dash-style defines a sequence representing the lengths of the dash segments. Alternate entries in the sequence represent the lengths of the opaque and transparent segments of the dashes. This corresponds to the strokeDashArray variable of Shape. The optional phase parameter defines the point in the dashing pattern that will correspond to the beginning of the stroke. This corresponds to the strokeDashOffset variable of Shape.
-fx-border-width <helper-border-width> A series of width or sets of four width values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single width value means that all border widths are the same; and if a set of four width values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left border widths, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first width value is used. Each item in the series of widths applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-image-source <helper-border-image-source> A series of image URIs, separated by commas.
-fx-border-image-insets <helper-border-image-insets> A series of inset or sets of four inset values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single inset value means that all insets are the same; and if a set of four inset values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order. Each item in the series of insets applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images.
-fx-border-image-repeat <helper-border-image-repeat> A series of repeat-style values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images.
-fx-border-image-slice <helper-border-image-slice> A series of image slice values or sets of four values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images. For each item in the series, if four values are given, they specify the size of the top, right, bottom, and left slices. This effectively divides the image into nine regions: an upper left corner, a top edge, an upper right corner, a right edge, a lower right corner, a bottom edge, a lower left corner, a left edge and a middle. If one value is specified, this value is used for the slice values for all four edges. If 'fill' is present, the middle slice is preserved, otherwise it is discarded. Percentage values may be used here, in which case the values are considered proportional to the source image.
-fx-border-image-width <helper-border-image-width> A series of width or sets of four width values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single width value means that all border widths are the same; and if a set of four width values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left border widths, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first width value is used. Each item in the series of widths applies to the corresponding item in the series of border images. Percentage values may be used here, in which case the values are considered proportional to the border image area.
-fx-padding <size> | <size> <size> <size> <size> A sets of four padding values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single padding value means that all padding are the same; and if a set of four padding values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order.
-fx-position-shape <boolean> true If true means the shape centered within the region's width and height, otherwise the shape is positioned at its source position. Has no effect if a shape string is not specified.
-fx-scale-shape <boolean> true If true means the shape is scaled to fit the size of the region, otherwise the shape is at its source size, and its position depends on the value of the position-shape property. Has no effect if a shape string is not specified.
-fx-shape <string> An SVG path string. By specifying a shape here the region takes on that shape instead of a rectangle or rounded rectangle. The syntax of this path string is specified in
-fx-snap-to-pixel <boolean> true Defines whether this region rounds position/spacing and ceils size values to pixel boundaries when laying out its children.
-fx-background-fills <helper-background-color> [ <helper-background-insets> || <helper-background-radius> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-background-color, optionally -fx-background-insets, and optionally -fx-background-radius. In order to set the background fill to null, specify the style "-fx-background-color: null;". There is no shorthand notation for -fx-background-fills at this time.
-fx-background-images <helper-background-image> [ <helper-background-position> || <helper-background-repeat> || <helper-background-size> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-background-image, optionally -fx-background-position, optionally -fx-background-repeat, and optionally -fx-background-size. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-background-images at this time.
-fx-stroke-borders <helper-border-color> [ <helper-border-insets> || <helper-border-radius> || <helper-border-style> || <helper-border-width> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-border-color with the optional -fx-border-insets, -fx-border-radius, -fx-border-style and -fx-border-width. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-stroke-borders at this time.
-fx-image-borders <helper-border-image-source> [ <helper-border-image-insets> || <helper-border-image-repeat> || <helper-border-image-slice> || <helper-border-image-width> ] null This property set by specifying -fx-border-image-source with the optional -fx-border-image-insets, -fx-border-image-repeat, -fx-border-image-slice and -fx-border-image-width. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-image-borders at this time.
Inherited Pseudo-Classes
Element Name Definition
Node :disabled applies when the disabled variable is true
:focused applies when the focused variable is true
:hover applies when the hover variable is true
:pressed applies when the pressed variable is true
:show-mnemonic apples when the mnemonic affordance (typically an underscore) should be shown.

BarChart extends XYChart

Description
A chart that plots bars indicating data values for a category. The bars can be vertical or horizontal depending on which axis is a category axis.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-bar-gap double 4 gap between bars
-fx-category-gap double 10 The gap to leave between bars in separate categories
Inherited Properties
Element Property Definition Default Description
Chart -fx-legend-side [ top | left | right | bottom ] bottom the side of the chart where the legend should be displayed
-fx-legend-visible <boolean> true When true the chart will display a legend if the chart implementation supports a legend.
-fx-title-side [ top | left | right | bottom ] top The side of the chart where the title is displayed
Node -fx-blend-mode <blend-mode> null The mode used to blend this individual node into the scene behind it
-fx-cursor <cursor> null Defines the mouse cursor for this Node and subnodes
-fx-effect <effect> null Specifies an effect to apply to this Node
-fx-focus-traversable <boolean> null Specifies whether this Node should be a part of focus traversal cycle
-fx-opacity double 1.0 Opacity can be thought of conceptually as a postprocessing operation. Conceptually, after the node (including its descendants) is rendered into an RGBA offscreen image, the opacity setting specifies how to blend the offscreen rendering into the current composite rendering.
-fx-rotate double 0.0 This is the angle of the rotation in degrees. Zero degrees is at 3 o'clock (directly to the right). Angle values are positive clockwise. Rotation is about the center.
-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-y double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Y axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.
-fx-translate-x double 0.0 Defines the x coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-y double 0.0 Defines the y coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-z double 0.0 Defines the z coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
visibility <visibility> visible
XYChart -fx-alternative-column-fill-visible <boolean> true If true then alternative vertical columns will have fills
-fx-alternative-row-fill-visible <boolean> true If true then alternative horizontal rows will have fills
-fx-horizontal-grid-lines-visible <boolean> true True if horizontal grid lines should be drawn
-fx-horizontal-zero-line-visible <boolean> true If this is true and the horizontal axis has both positive and negative values then a additional axis line will be drawn at the zero point
-fx-vertical-grid-lines-visible <boolean> true True if vertical grid lines should be drawn
-fx-vertical-zero-line-visible <boolean> true If this is true and the vertical axis has both positive and negative values then a additional axis line will be drawn at the zero point

Each item in the series of insets applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-radius <helper-border-radius> A series of radius or sets of four radius values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single radius value means that all corner radii are the same; and if a set of four radius values is specified, they are used as the radii of the top-left, top-right, bottom-right, and bottom-left corners, in that order. Each item in the series of radii applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-style <helper-border-style> A series of border style values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors. The segments dash-style defines a sequence representing the lengths of the dash segments. Alternate entries in the sequence represent the lengths of the opaque and transparent segments of the dashes. This corresponds to the strokeDashArray variable of Shape. The optional phase parameter defines the point in the dashing pattern that will correspond to the beginning of the stroke. This corresponds to the strokeDashOffset variable of Shape.
-fx-border-width <helper-border-width> A series of width or sets of four width values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single width value means that all border widths are the same; and if a set of four width values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left border widths, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first width value is used. Each item in the series of widths applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-image-source <helper-border-image-source> A series of image URIs, separated by commas.
-fx-border-image-insets <helper-border-image-insets> A series of inset or sets of four inset values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single inset value means that all insets are the same; and if a set of four inset values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order. Each item in the series of insets applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images.
-fx-border-image-repeat <helper-border-image-repeat> A series of repeat-style values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images.
-fx-border-image-slice <helper-border-image-slice> A series of image slice values or sets of four values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images. For each item in the series, if four values are given, they specify the size of the top, right, bottom, and left slices. This effectively divides the image into nine regions: an upper left corner, a top edge, an upper right corner, a right edge, a lower right corner, a bottom edge, a lower left corner, a left edge and a middle. If one value is specified, this value is used for the slice values for all four edges. If 'fill' is present, the middle slice is preserved, otherwise it is discarded. Percentage values may be used here, in which case the values are considered proportional to the source image.
-fx-border-image-width <helper-border-image-width> A series of width or sets of four width values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single width value means that all border widths are the same; and if a set of four width values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left border widths, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first width value is used. Each item in the series of widths applies to the corresponding item in the series of border images. Percentage values may be used here, in which case the values are considered proportional to the border image area.
-fx-padding <size> | <size> <size> <size> <size> A sets of four padding values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single padding value means that all padding are the same; and if a set of four padding values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order.
-fx-position-shape <boolean> true If true means the shape centered within the region's width and height, otherwise the shape is positioned at its source position. Has no effect if a shape string is not specified.
-fx-scale-shape <boolean> true If true means the shape is scaled to fit the size of the region, otherwise the shape is at its source size, and its position depends on the value of the position-shape property. Has no effect if a shape string is not specified.
-fx-shape <string> An SVG path string. By specifying a shape here the region takes on that shape instead of a rectangle or rounded rectangle. The syntax of this path string is specified in
-fx-snap-to-pixel <boolean> true Defines whether this region rounds position/spacing and ceils size values to pixel boundaries when laying out its children.
-fx-background-fills <helper-background-color> [ <helper-background-insets> || <helper-background-radius> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-background-color, optionally -fx-background-insets, and optionally -fx-background-radius. In order to set the background fill to null, specify the style "-fx-background-color: null;". There is no shorthand notation for -fx-background-fills at this time.
-fx-background-images <helper-background-image> [ <helper-background-position> || <helper-background-repeat> || <helper-background-size> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-background-image, optionally -fx-background-position, optionally -fx-background-repeat, and optionally -fx-background-size. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-background-images at this time.
-fx-stroke-borders <helper-border-color> [ <helper-border-insets> || <helper-border-radius> || <helper-border-style> || <helper-border-width> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-border-color with the optional -fx-border-insets, -fx-border-radius, -fx-border-style and -fx-border-width. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-stroke-borders at this time.
-fx-image-borders <helper-border-image-source> [ <helper-border-image-insets> || <helper-border-image-repeat> || <helper-border-image-slice> || <helper-border-image-width> ] null This property set by specifying -fx-border-image-source with the optional -fx-border-image-insets, -fx-border-image-repeat, -fx-border-image-slice and -fx-border-image-width. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-image-borders at this time.
Inherited Pseudo-Classes
Element Name Definition
Node :disabled applies when the disabled variable is true
:focused applies when the focused variable is true
:hover applies when the hover variable is true
:pressed applies when the pressed variable is true
:show-mnemonic apples when the mnemonic affordance (typically an underscore) should be shown.

LineChart extends XYChart

Description
Line Chart plots a line connecting the data points in a series. The data points themselves can be represented by symbols optionally. Line charts are usually used to view data trends over time or category.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-create-symbols <boolean> true Indicates whether symbols for data points will be created or not.
Inherited Properties
Element Property Definition Default Description
Chart -fx-legend-side [ top | left | right | bottom ] bottom the side of the chart where the legend should be displayed
-fx-legend-visible <boolean> true When true the chart will display a legend if the chart implementation supports a legend.
-fx-title-side [ top | left | right | bottom ] top The side of the chart where the title is displayed
Node -fx-blend-mode <blend-mode> null The mode used to blend this individual node into the scene behind it
-fx-cursor <cursor> null Defines the mouse cursor for this Node and subnodes
-fx-effect <effect> null Specifies an effect to apply to this Node
-fx-focus-traversable <boolean> null Specifies whether this Node should be a part of focus traversal cycle
-fx-opacity double 1.0 Opacity can be thought of conceptually as a postprocessing operation. Conceptually, after the node (including its descendants) is rendered into an RGBA offscreen image, the opacity setting specifies how to blend the offscreen rendering into the current composite rendering.
-fx-rotate double 0.0 This is the angle of the rotation in degrees. Zero degrees is at 3 o'clock (directly to the right). Angle values are positive clockwise. Rotation is about the center.
-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-y double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Y axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.
-fx-translate-x double 0.0 Defines the x coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-y double 0.0 Defines the y coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-z double 0.0 Defines the z coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
visibility <visibility> visible
XYChart -fx-alternative-column-fill-visible <boolean> true If true then alternative vertical columns will have fills

PieChart extends Chart

Description
Displays a PieChart. The chart content is populated by pie slices based on data set on the PieChart.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-clockwise <boolean> true When true we start placing slices clockwise from the startAngle
-fx-pie-label-visible <boolean> true When true pie slice labels are drawn
-fx-label-line-length <size> 20 The length of the line from the outside of the pie to the slice labels.
-fx-start-angle double 0.0 The angle to start the first pie slice at

-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-y double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Y axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.
-fx-translate-x double 0.0 Defines the x coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-y double 0.0 Defines the y coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-z double 0.0 Defines the z coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
visibility <visibility> visible
Region -fx-background-color <helper-background-color> null A series of paint values separated by commas.
-fx-background-insets <helper-background-insets> null A series of size values or sets of four size values, separated by commas. A single size value means all insets are the same. Otherwise, the four values for each inset are given in the order top, right, bottom, left. Each comma-separated value or set of values in the series applies to the corresponding background color.
-fx-background-image <helper-background-image> null A series of image URIs separated by commas.
-fx-background-position <helper-background-position> null A series of values separated by commas. Each bg-position item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the background-image series.
-fx-background-repeat <helper-background-repeat> null
-fx-background-size <helper-background-size>
-fx-border-color <helper-border-color> A series of paint values or sets of four paint values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, if a single paint value is specified, then that paint is used as the border for all sides of the region; and if a set of four paints is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left borders of the region, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first paint value in the set is used.
-fx-border-insets <helper-border-insets> A series of inset or sets of four inset values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single inset value means that all insets are the same; and if a set of four inset values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order. Each item in the series of insets applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-radius <helper-border-radius> A series of radius or sets of four radius values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single radius value means that all corner radii are the same; and if a set of four radius values is specified, they are used as the radii of the top-left, top-right, bottom-right, and bottom-left corners, in that order. Each item in the series of radii applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-style <helper-border-style> A series of border style values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors. The segments dash-style defines a sequence representing the lengths of the dash segments. Alternate entries in the sequence represent the lengths of the opaque and transparent segments of the dashes. This corresponds to the strokeDashArray variable of Shape. The optional phase parameter defines the point in the dashing pattern that will correspond to the beginning of the stroke. This corresponds to the strokeDashOffset variable of Shape.
-fx-border-width <helper-border-width> A series of width or sets of four width values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single width value means that all border widths are the same; and if a set of four width values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left border widths, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first width value is used. Each item in the series of widths applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-image-source <helper-border-image-source> A series of image URIs, separated by commas.
-fx-border-image-insets <helper-border-image-insets> A series of inset or sets of four inset values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single inset value means that all insets are the same; and if a set of four inset values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order. Each item in the series of insets applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images.
-fx-border-image-repeat <helper-border-image-repeat> A series of repeat-style values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images.
-fx-border-image-slice <helper-border-image-slice> A series of image slice values or sets of four values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images. For each item in the series, if four values are given, they specify the size of the top, right, bottom, and left slices. This effectively divides the image into nine regions: an upper left corner, a top edge, an upper right corner, a right edge, a lower right corner, a bottom edge, a lower left corner, a left edge and a middle. If one value is specified, this value is used for the slice values for all four edges. If 'fill' is present, the middle slice is preserved, otherwise it is discarded. Percentage values may be used here, in which case the values are considered proportional to the source image.
-fx-border-image-width <helper-border-image-width> A series of width or sets of four width values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single width value means that all border widths are the same; and if a set of four width values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left border widths, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first width value is used. Each item in the series of widths applies to the corresponding item in the series of border images. Percentage values may be used here, in which case the values are considered proportional to the border image area.
-fx-padding <size> | <size> <size> <size> <size> A sets of four padding values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single padding value means that all padding are the same; and if a set of four padding values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order.
-fx-position-shape <boolean> true If true means the shape centered within the region's width and height, otherwise the shape is positioned at its source position. Has no effect if a shape string is not specified.
-fx-scale-shape <boolean> true If true means the shape is scaled to fit the size of the region, otherwise the shape is at its source size, and its position depends on the value of the position-shape property. Has no effect if a shape string is not specified.
-fx-shape <string> An SVG path string. By specifying a shape here the region takes on that shape instead of a rectangle or rounded rectangle. The syntax of this path string is specified in
-fx-snap-to-pixel <boolean> true Defines whether this region rounds position/spacing and ceils size values to pixel boundaries when laying out its children.
-fx-background-fills <helper-background-color> [ <helper-background-insets> || <helper-background-radius> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-background-color, optionally -fx-background-insets, and optionally -fx-background-radius. In order to set the background fill to null, specify the style "-fx-background-color: null;". There is no shorthand notation for -fx-background-fills at this time.
-fx-background-images <helper-background-image> [ <helper-background-position> || <helper-background-repeat> || <helper-background-size> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-background-image, optionally -fx-background-position, optionally -fx-background-repeat, and optionally -fx-background-size. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-background-images at this time.
-fx-stroke-borders <helper-border-color> [ <helper-border-insets> || <helper-border-radius> || <helper-border-style> || <helper-border-width> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-border-color with the optional -fx-border-insets, -fx-border-radius, -fx-border-style and -fx-border-width. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-stroke-borders at this time.
-fx-image-borders <helper-border-image-source> [ <helper-border-image-insets> || <helper-border-image-repeat> || <helper-border-image-slice> || <helper-border-image-width> ] null This property set by specifying -fx-border-image-source with the optional -fx-border-image-insets, -fx-border-image-repeat, -fx-border-image-slice and -fx-border-image-width. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-image-borders at this time.
Inherited Pseudo-Classes
Element Name Definition
Node :disabled applies when the disabled variable is true
:focused applies when the focused variable is true
:hover applies when the hover variable is true
:pressed applies when the pressed variable is true
:show-mnemonic apples when the mnemonic affordance (typically an underscore) should be shown.

XYChart extends Chart

Description
Chart base class for all 2 axis charts. It is responsible for drawing the two axes and the plot content. It contains a list of all content in the plot and implementations of XYChart can add nodes to this list that need to be rendered.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-alternative-column-fill-visible <boolean> true If true then alternative vertical columns will have fills
-fx-alternative-row-fill-visible <boolean> true If true then alternative horizontal rows will have fills
-fx-horizontal-grid-lines-visible <boolean> true True if horizontal grid lines should be drawn
-fx-horizontal-zero-line-visible <boolean> true If this is true and the horizontal axis has both positive and negative values then a additional axis line will be drawn at the zero point
-fx-vertical-grid-lines-visible <boolean> true True if vertical grid lines should be drawn
-fx-vertical-zero-line-visible <boolean> true If this is true and the vertical axis has both positive and negative values then a additional axis line will be drawn at the zero point
Inherited Properties
Element Property Definition Default Description
Chart -fx-legend-side [ top | left | right | bottom ] bottom the side of the chart where the legend should be displayed
-fx-legend-visible <boolean> true When true the chart will display a legend if the chart implementation supports a legend.
-fx-title-side [ top | left | right | bottom ] top The side of the chart where the title is displayed
Node -fx-blend-mode <blend-mode> null The mode used to blend this individual node into the scene behind it
-fx-cursor <cursor> null Defines the mouse cursor for this Node and subnodes
-fx-effect <effect> null Specifies an effect to apply to this Node
-fx-focus-traversable <boolean> null Specifies whether this Node should be a part of focus traversal cycle
-fx-opacity double 1.0 Opacity can be thought of conceptually as a postprocessing operation. Conceptually, after the node (including its descendants) is rendered into an RGBA offscreen image, the opacity setting specifies how to blend the offscreen rendering into the current composite rendering.
-fx-rotate double 0.0 This is the angle of the rotation in degrees. Zero degrees is at 3 o'clock (directly to the right). Angle values are positive clockwise. Rotation is about the center.
-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-y double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Y axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.
-fx-translate-x double 0.0 Defines the x coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-y double 0.0 Defines the y coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-z double 0.0 Defines the z coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.

Axis extends Region

Description
Base class for all axes in JavaFX that represents an axis drawn on a chart area.
Properties

-fx-tick-label-fill <paint> 8 The fill for all tick labels
-fx-tick-label-gap <size> 8 The gap between tick labels and the tick mark lines
-fx-tick-mark-visible <boolean> true true if tick marks should be displayed
-fx-tick-labels-visible <boolean> true true if tick mark labels should be displayed

ValueAxis extends Axis

Description
A axis who's data is defined as Numbers. It can also draw minor tick-marks between the major ones.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-minor-tick-length <size> 5 The length of minor tick mark lines. Set to 0 to not display minor tick marks.
-fx-minor-tick-count <size> 5 The number of minor tick divisions to be displayed between each major tick mark. The number of actual minor tick marks will be one less than this.
-fx-minor-tick-visible <boolean> true true if minor tick marks should be displayed
Inherited Properties
Element Property Definition Default Description
Node -fx-blend-mode <blend-mode> null The mode used to blend this individual node into the scene behind it
-fx-cursor <cursor> null Defines the mouse cursor for this Node and subnodes
-fx-effect <effect> null Specifies an effect to apply to this Node
-fx-focus-traversable <boolean> null Specifies whether this Node should be a part of focus traversal cycle
-fx-opacity double 1.0 Opacity can be thought of conceptually as a postprocessing operation. Conceptually, after the node (including its descendants) is rendered into an RGBA offscreen image, the opacity setting specifies how to blend the offscreen rendering into the current composite rendering.
-fx-rotate double 0.0 This is the angle of the rotation in degrees. Zero degrees is at 3 o'clock (directly to the right). Angle values are positive clockwise. Rotation is about the center.
-fx-scale-x double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the X axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-y double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Y axis of this Node.
-fx-scale-z double 1 Defines the factor by which coordinates are scaled about the center of the object along the Z axis of this Node.
-fx-translate-x double 0.0 Defines the x coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-y double 0.0 Defines the y coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
-fx-translate-z double 0.0 Defines the z coordinate of the translation that is added to this Node's transform.
visibility <visibility> visible
Region -fx-background-color <helper-background-color> null A series of paint values separated by commas.
-fx-background-insets <helper-background-insets> null A series of size values or sets of four size values, separated by commas. A single size value means all insets are the same. Otherwise, the four values for each inset are given in the order top, right, bottom, left. Each comma-separated value or set of values in the series applies to the corresponding background color.
-fx-background-image <helper-background-image> null A series of image URIs separated by commas.
-fx-background-position <helper-background-position> null A series of values separated by commas. Each bg-position item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the background-image series.
-fx-background-repeat <helper-background-repeat> null
-fx-background-size <helper-background-size>
-fx-border-color <helper-border-color> A series of paint values or sets of four paint values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, if a single paint value is specified, then that paint is used as the border for all sides of the region; and if a set of four paints is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left borders of the region, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first paint value in the set is used.
-fx-border-insets <helper-border-insets> A series of inset or sets of four inset values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single inset value means that all insets are the same; and if a set of four inset values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order. Each item in the series of insets applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-radius <helper-border-radius> A series of radius or sets of four radius values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single radius value means that all corner radii are the same; and if a set of four radius values is specified, they are used as the radii of the top-left, top-right, bottom-right, and bottom-left corners, in that order. Each item in the series of radii applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-style <helper-border-style> A series of border style values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors. The segments dash-style defines a sequence representing the lengths of the dash segments. Alternate entries in the sequence represent the lengths of the opaque and transparent segments of the dashes. This corresponds to the strokeDashArray variable of Shape. The optional phase parameter defines the point in the dashing pattern that will correspond to the beginning of the stroke. This corresponds to the strokeDashOffset variable of Shape.
-fx-border-width <helper-border-width> A series of width or sets of four width values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single width value means that all border widths are the same; and if a set of four width values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left border widths, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first width value is used. Each item in the series of widths applies to the corresponding item in the series of border colors.
-fx-border-image-source <helper-border-image-source> A series of image URIs, separated by commas.
-fx-border-image-insets <helper-border-image-insets> A series of inset or sets of four inset values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single inset value means that all insets are the same; and if a set of four inset values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order. Each item in the series of insets applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images.
-fx-border-image-repeat <helper-border-image-repeat> A series of repeat-style values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images.
-fx-border-image-slice <helper-border-image-slice> A series of image slice values or sets of four values, separated by commas. Each item in the series applies to the corresponding image in the series of border images. For each item in the series, if four values are given, they specify the size of the top, right, bottom, and left slices. This effectively divides the image into nine regions: an upper left corner, a top edge, an upper right corner, a right edge, a lower right corner, a bottom edge, a lower left corner, a left edge and a middle. If one value is specified, this value is used for the slice values for all four edges. If 'fill' is present, the middle slice is preserved, otherwise it is discarded. Percentage values may be used here, in which case the values are considered proportional to the source image.
-fx-border-image-width <helper-border-image-width> A series of width or sets of four width values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single width value means that all border widths are the same; and if a set of four width values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left border widths, in that order. If the border is not rectangular, only the first width value is used. Each item in the series of widths applies to the corresponding item in the series of border images. Percentage values may be used here, in which case the values are considered proportional to the border image area.
-fx-padding <size> | <size> <size> <size> <size> A sets of four padding values, separated by commas. For each item in the series, a single padding value means that all padding are the same; and if a set of four padding values is specified, they are used for the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the region, in that order.
-fx-position-shape <boolean> true If true means the shape centered within the region's width and height, otherwise the shape is positioned at its source position. Has no effect if a shape string is not specified.
-fx-scale-shape <boolean> true If true means the shape is scaled to fit the size of the region, otherwise the shape is at its source size, and its position depends on the value of the position-shape property. Has no effect if a shape string is not specified.
-fx-shape <string> An SVG path string. By specifying a shape here the region takes on that shape instead of a rectangle or rounded rectangle. The syntax of this path string is specified in
-fx-snap-to-pixel <boolean> true Defines whether this region rounds position/spacing and ceils size values to pixel boundaries when laying out its children.
-fx-background-fills <helper-background-color> [ <helper-background-insets> || <helper-background-radius> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-background-color, optionally -fx-background-insets, and optionally -fx-background-radius. In order to set the background fill to null, specify the style "-fx-background-color: null;". There is no shorthand notation for -fx-background-fills at this time.
-fx-background-images <helper-background-image> [ <helper-background-position> || <helper-background-repeat> || <helper-background-size> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-background-image, optionally -fx-background-position, optionally -fx-background-repeat, and optionally -fx-background-size. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-background-images at this time.
-fx-stroke-borders <helper-border-color> [ <helper-border-insets> || <helper-border-radius> || <helper-border-style> || <helper-border-width> ] null This property is set by specifying -fx-border-color with the optional -fx-border-insets, -fx-border-radius, -fx-border-style and -fx-border-width. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-stroke-borders at this time.
-fx-image-borders <helper-border-image-source> [ <helper-border-image-insets> || <helper-border-image-repeat> || <helper-border-image-slice> || <helper-border-image-width> ] null This property set by specifying -fx-border-image-source with the optional -fx-border-image-insets, -fx-border-image-repeat, -fx-border-image-slice and -fx-border-image-width. There is no shorthand notation for -fx-image-borders at this time.
Axis -fx-side [ top | left | right | bottom ] null The side of the plot which this axis is being drawn on
-fx-tick-length <size> 8 The length of tick mark lines
-fx-tick-label-font <font> 8 The font for all tick labels
-fx-tick-label-fill <paint> 8 The fill for all tick labels
-fx-tick-label-gap <size> 8 The gap between tick labels and the tick mark lines
-fx-tick-mark-visible <boolean> true true if tick marks should be displayed
-fx-tick-labels-visible <boolean> true true if tick mark labels should be displayed
Inherited Pseudo-Classes
Element Name Definition
Node :disabled applies when the disabled variable is true
:focused applies when the focused variable is true
:hover applies when the hover variable is true
:pressed applies when the pressed variable is true
:show-mnemonic apples when the mnemonic affordance (typically an underscore) should be shown.

NumberAxis extends ValueAxis

Description
A axis class that plots a range of numbers with major tick marks every "tickUnit". You can use any Number type with this axis, Long, Double, BigDecimal etc.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-tick-unit double 5 The value between each major tick mark in data units.

CategoryAxis extends Axis

Description
A axis implementation that will works on string categories where each value as a unique category(tick mark) along the axis.
Properties
Property Definition Default Description
-fx-start-margin double 5 The margin between the axis start and the first tick-mark
-fx-end-margin double 5 The margin between the axis start and the first tick-mark
-fx-gap-start-and-end <boolean> true If this is true then half the space between ticks is left at the start and end

There is no shorthand notation for -fx-stroke-borders at this time.
